"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/897224","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-05-14","<p>No civil servants within the Department are provided with an official car and driver.</p>","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse",,"2018-05-14T13:39:40.743Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/897224/answer","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/897224/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/897224/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-05-03","Department for Work and Pensions: Official Cars","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what the job titles are of civil servants in her Department who have been provided with (a) an official car and (b) a driver.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","141012"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/897225","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-05-14","<p>Within the Department, no civil servants have a designated official car or driver. The Chief Medical Officer has access to an official Government car and driver from a shared cross government service. This has been used on occasions where there has been a need to make confidential or sensitive telephone calls whilst travelling and where it would be inappropriate to do so whilst travelling on public transport.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2018-05-14T11:16:23.627Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/897225/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/897225/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/897225/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-05-03","Department of Health and Social Care: Official Cars","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what the job titles are of civil servants in his Department who have been provided with (a) an official car and (b) a driver.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","141013"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/897226","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-05-10","<p>Ministry of Defence (MOD) policy is that, generally, official cars are pooled rather than allocated. No MOD civil servants currently have a dedicated driver.</p><p>A small number of officials are, however, provided with a car to enable them to carry out essential duties. This includes some chaplains, welfare officers, recruiters, safety inspectors, housing officers and security staff.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2018-05-10T15:05:49.057Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/897226/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/897226/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/897226/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-05-03","Ministry of Defence: Official Cars","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what the job titles are of civil servants in his Department who have been provided with (a) an official car and (b) a driver.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","141014"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/897227","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-05-14","<p>No civil servants in the Ministry of Justice are provided with an official car or driver. Civil servants may on occasion travel in an official vehicle as part of a specific duty, for example, accompanying Ministers on Ministerial visits.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2018-05-14T16:40:47.683Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/897227/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/897227/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/897227/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-05-03","Ministry of Justice: Official Cars","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what the job titles are of civil servants in his Department who have been provided with (a) an official car and (b) a driver.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","141015"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/897228","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-05-15","<p>The Department has no current assessment on how level letter boxes effect postal workers. The statutory guidance which supports the Building Regulations references industry technical guidance which in turn refers to a British and European standard (BS EN 134724: 2013). This standard recommends a range for letter box apertures to be within a height range of 700 millimetres up to 1700 millimetres.</p><p>The statutory guidance which support Building Regulations references the Door and Hardware Federation’s technical specification TS 008: 2012, which in turn refers to a British and European standard relating to letter boxes: BS EN 134724: 2013.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab","140989","2018-05-15T16:01:49.313Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/897228/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/897228/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/897228/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-05-03","Letter Boxes: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, what steps he is taking to ensure that letter boxes confirm with European Standard EN 13724.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","140988"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/897229","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-05-15","<p>The Department has no current assessment on how level letter boxes effect postal workers. The statutory guidance which supports the Building Regulations references industry technical guidance which in turn refers to a British and European standard (BS EN 134724: 2013). This standard recommends a range for letter box apertures to be within a height range of 700 millimetres up to 1700 millimetres.</p><p>The statutory guidance which support Building Regulations references the Door and Hardware Federation’s technical specification TS 008: 2012, which in turn refers to a British and European standard relating to letter boxes: BS EN 134724: 2013.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab","140988","2018-05-15T16:01:49.39Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/897229/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/897229/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/897229/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-05-03","Letter Boxes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, what assessment he has made of the physical effect on postal workers of properties with low level letterboxes.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","140989"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/897230","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-05-14","<p>​The UK is supporting election monitoring in Bangladesh by funding short and long term domestic observers through a Department for International Development programme. We have not to date received any request from the Bangladesh Government to deploy our own election monitors. We shall continue to engage with the Government of Bangladesh, the Election Commission and political parties on the need for robust democratic mechanisms and the proper application of election law during the general election which we understand will take place at the end of 2018.</p>","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field",,"2018-05-14T12:13:06.367Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/897230/answer","Biography information for Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/897230/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/897230/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-05-03","Bangladesh: Elections","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, whether the Government will have a role in monitoring the forthcoming general election in Bangladesh.","false","Biography information for Mrs Anne Main","St Albans","Mrs Anne Main","141017"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/897231","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-05-14","<p>​I remain concerned that the imprisonment of Khaleda Zia, the main opposition leader in Bangladesh, impedes an effective dialogue between the main parties and could increase the risk of violence around the election which as a consequence may not be fully participatory. The Foreign Secretary met Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina and Foreign Minister Ali during his visit to Bangladesh from 9 to 10 February. He stressed the importance of free and fair elections and affording political space to the opposition.</p>","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field",,"2018-05-14T12:21:44.94Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/897231/answer","Biography information for Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/897231/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/897231/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-05-03","Bangladesh: Politics and Government","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment he has made of the effect of the imprisonment of the main opposition party leader in Bangladesh on free, fair, and transparent electoral processes in that country.","false","Biography information for Mrs Anne Main","St Albans","Mrs Anne Main","141018"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/897232","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-05-14","<p>​The FCO is keen to see accurate voter registration lists compiled and updated throughout Bangladesh in advance of the forthcoming general election, this is why we have called on the Government of Bangladesh and opposition parties to allow the Election Commission to carry out its important work independently and free of political interference.</p><p> </p>","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field",,"2018-05-14T12:24:00.893Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/897232/answer","Biography information for Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/897232/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/897232/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-05-03","Bangladesh: Elections","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what progress has been made on voter registration in rural areas in Bangladesh for the forthcoming general election in that country.","false","Biography information for Mrs Anne Main","St Albans","Mrs Anne Main","141019"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/897233","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-05-14","<p>​<strong>I met Foreign Minister Ali on 19 April in the margins of the Commonwealth Heads of Government Meeting and during a 30 minute long meeting we discussed amongst other issues the importance of free, fair and participatory elections in Bangladesh. </strong></p>","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field",,"2018-05-14T12:25:55.513Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/897233/answer","Biography information for Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/897233/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/897233/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-05-03","Bangladesh: Elections","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions he has had with representatives of the Bangladesh Government at the recent Commonwealth Heads of Government Meeting in London on ensuring free and fair elections in that country.","false","Biography information for Mrs Anne Main","St Albans","Mrs Anne Main","141020"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/897234","Department for Transport","false","2018-05-09","<p>The Oxford to Cambridge Expressway will be subject to an Environmental Impact Assessment. A Strategic Environmental Assessment will not be required.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2018-05-09T12:50:16.647Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/897234/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/897234/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/897234/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-05-03","Roads: Construction","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether he has taken steps to commission a strategic environmental assessment for the proposed routes for the Oxford to Cambridge Expressway.","false","Biography information for Dame Cheryl Gillan","Chesham and Amersham","Dame Cheryl Gillan","140978"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/897235","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-05-10","<p>Chapter 2 of the annual Digest of UK Energy Statistics (DUKES) includes data on coal reserves broken down by planning permission stage. The latest data for 2017 is available here (Table 2C):</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/solid-fuels-and-derived-gases-chapter-2-digest-of-united-kingdom-energy-statistics-dukes" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/solid-fuels-and-derived-gases-chapter-2-digest-of-united-kingdom-energy-statistics-dukes</a></p><p> </p><p>Historical editions of DUKES are available here:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/digest-of-uk-energy-statistics-dukes" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/digest-of-uk-energy-statistics-dukes</a></p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2018-05-10T14:34:51.103Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/897235/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/897235/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/897235/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-05-03","Coal: Reserves","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what estimate he has made of the amount of coal reserves that have planning permission to be mined for each year since 2010; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","141016"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/897236","Department for International Trade","false","2018-05-09","<p>We are currently talking to a number of countries on a variety of future trading options, which could include new Free Trade Agreements (FTAs). As a priority, we are working to secure continuity for our existing EU trade agreements with over 70 countries.</p><p>In accordance with the terms of the draft Withdrawal Agreement, we will be able to negotiate, sign and ratify new trade agreements after we leave the EU in March 2019, allowing us to establish and enhance our trading relationships with old allies and new friends.</p><p> </p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2018-05-09T14:14:36.3Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/897236/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/897236/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/897236/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2018-05-03","Trade Agreements","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, how many preferential trade agreements he plans to have (a) in draft and (b) agreed with which countries by March 2019.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","140981"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/897237","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-05-09","<p>The change in the number of delayed transfers of care at Brighton and Sussex University Hospitals NHS Trust between 2015 and 2017, disaggregated by the reason for the delay, is shown in the table below:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>2017</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Completion of assessment</p></td><td><p>93</p></td><td><p>1,886</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Public funding</p></td><td><p>191</p></td><td><p>541</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Waiting further National Health Service non- acute care</p></td><td><p>4,624</p></td><td><p>7,890</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Awaiting residential home placement or availability</p></td><td><p>1,018</p></td><td><p>1,542</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Awaiting nursing home placement or availability</p></td><td><p>1,297</p></td><td><p>3,025</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Awaiting care package in own home</p></td><td><p>2,265</p></td><td><p>5,051</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Awaiting community equipment and adaptations</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>466</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Patient or family choice</p></td><td><p>2,354</p></td><td><p>1,001</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Disputes</p></td><td><p>65</p></td><td><p>807</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Housing- patients not covered by NHS and Community Care Act</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>563</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>Source: <a href="https://www.england.nhs.uk/statistics/statistical-work-areas/delayed-transfers-of-care/" target="_blank">https://www.england.nhs.uk/statistics/statistical-work-areas/delayed-transfers-of-care/</a></p><p> </p><p>During 2017/18, there have been a number of actions and developments put in place to help reduce delays at the Trust. These include the identification of onward care capacity, improvements in communication and relationships with care homes and the roll-out of pathways to support early discharge.</p><p> </p><p>The latest data for February 2018 shows that the number of delayed days at the Trust is now 1,200, a reduction of 1,052 delayed days compared to the same month in 2017.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2018-05-09T15:10:01.02Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/897237/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/897237/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/897237/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-05-03","Brighton and Sussex University Hospitals NHS Trust","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, pursuant to the Answer of 2 May, 2018 to Question 138935 and with reference to the Answer of 26 May 2016 to Question 38904, to what he attributes the increase of 10,865 in the number of bed days lost due to delayed transfers of care in Brighton and Sussex University Hospitals NHS Trust in 2017 compared with 2015.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","140982"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/897238","Department for Transport","false","2018-05-09","<p>I can confirm that there will be no cost incurred by the taxpayer as a result of this error. The supplier responsible for distributing notifications will cover the cost of the original erroneous correspondence.</p>","Wealden","Ms Nusrat Ghani",,"2018-05-09T12:53:39.767Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/897238/answer","Biography information for Ms Nusrat Ghani","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/897238/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/897238/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-05-03","High Speed Two: Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the cost to the public purse was of the administrative error that resulted in personalised envelopes and communications being sent to people in Garthdee and Ferryhill in Scotland on work due to take place in Calvert in Buckinghamshire.","false","Biography information for Dame Cheryl Gillan","Chesham and Amersham","Dame Cheryl Gillan","140979"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/897239","Department for Transport","false","2018-05-14","<p>HS2 Ltd are investigating a technical error that unfortunately resulted in notices being sent to incorrect addresses, and are reviewing the process and systems used to distribute resident correspondence to ensure that this doesn’t happen again<em>.</em></p>","Wealden","Ms Nusrat Ghani",,"2018-05-14T15:00:07.363Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/897239/answer","Biography information for Ms Nusrat Ghani","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/897239/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/897239/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-05-03","High Speed Two: Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the reasons were for notices relating to work on High Speed Two in Birmingham being sent to residents in Scotland; and what steps his Department is taking to ensure that communications errors on High Speed Two are not repeated.","false","Biography information for Dame Cheryl Gillan","Chesham and Amersham","Dame Cheryl Gillan","140980"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/897240","Department for Education","false","2018-05-14","<p>Local authorities are not required to provide specific data regarding spend on children provided with support under section 17 of the Children Act 1989. However, the Department for Education collects data on local authority spend on a range of services for children and young people.</p><p> </p><p>The data table below shows local authority gross spend that may be on children in need but may also provide services to children not assessed as needing support under section 17. The data is for 2016-17. Data on local authority spend on children and young people services in 2017-18 will be published in autumn 2018.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p><strong>2016-17 (£000’s)</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Child Protection and Safeguarding</p></td><td><p>£2,334,268</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Children’s Centres and Other Spend on Children Under 5</p></td><td><p>£774,349</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Family Support</p></td><td><p>£1,087,140</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Other Children and Families Services</p></td><td><p>£87,175</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Services for Young People</p></td><td><p>£447,532</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Source: Section 251 Outturn</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi",,"2018-05-14T16:42:41.313Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/897240/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/897240/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/897240/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-05-03","Children: Social Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how much has been spent from the public purse under section 17 of the Children’s Act 1989 by public bodies in 2017-2018.","false","Biography information for Mrs Emma Lewell-Buck","South Shields","Mrs Emma Lewell-Buck","141026"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/897241","Department for Education","false","2018-05-14","<p>The Education and Skills Funding Agency publishes the 16 to 19-year olds funding allocations data for individual institutions annually. This includes the amount of disadvantage funding allocated to each institution. Further information on allocations is available at GOV.UK: <a href="http://www.gov.uk/guidance/16-to-19-education-funding-allocations#published-allocations" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/guidance/16-to-19-education-funding-allocations#published-allocations</a>.</p><p> </p><p>The department does not collect data on how institutions spend the disadvantage portion of their allocations.</p>","Guildford","Anne Milton",,"2018-05-14T16:20:21.657Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/897241/answer","Biography information for Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/897241/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/897241/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-05-03","Schools: Expenditure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, which (a) schools and (b) colleges received funding from the £520 million allocated by his Department to disadvantaged students aged 16-19 years old; and how much of that funding was spend by each institution.","false","Biography information for Mrs Emma Lewell-Buck","South Shields","Mrs Emma Lewell-Buck","141027"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/897242","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-05-14","<p>As the calendar year 2018 is incomplete at the time of response, figures for 2018 are not included in the tables below.</p><p> </p><p>Table 1 provides the number of Funeral Expenses Payments (FEP) applications received and the number of initial refusals in each year between 2015 and 2017.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong>Table 1: FEP applications received and initial refusals, 2015-2017</strong></p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>2016</p></td><td><p>2017</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Applications received</p></td><td><p>46,600</p></td><td><p>44,300</p></td><td><p>41,800</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Initial refusals</p></td><td><p>20,800</p></td><td><p>19,400</p></td><td><p>16,900</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Source: Policy, Budget and Management Information System</p><p> </p><p><strong>Notes to table 1: </strong></p><p> </p><ul><li><p>Figures are rounded to the nearest 100.</p></li><li><p>Due to the timing of application processing, figures on initial refusals may relate to applications received in the previous year.</p></li><li><p>These figures do not include applications which were processed clerically and have not been entered on to the Social Fund Computer System.</p></li><li><p>Figures on applications made are based on applications received by DWP, not applications processed. Some applications may have been withdrawn before a decision was made.</p></li><li><p>The number of applications made in each year is not equal to the number of people who made applications in that year. An individual may make multiple applications in a given time period.</p></li><li><p>The number of initial refusals gives the number of initially unsuccessful applications and not those that are unsuccessful after appeal. An application will only be unsuccessful if it does not meet the qualifying criteria. These include, amongst other criteria, being in receipt of relevant benefits and meeting rules regarding relationship with the deceased. The full qualifying criteria are outlined in section 7 of “The Social Fund: Technical Guidance” publication. (<a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/the-social-fund-technical-guidance/the-social-fund-technical-guidance" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/the-social-fund-technical-guidance/the-social-fund-technical-guidance</a>)</p></li></ul><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Table 2 provides the average FEP award in each year 2015-2017.</p><p> </p><p><strong>Table 2: Average FEP award, 2015-2017</strong></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>2016</p></td><td><p>2017</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Average award</p></td><td><p>£1,390</p></td><td><p>£1,420</p></td><td><p>£1,450</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Source: Policy, Budget and Management Information System</p><p> </p><p><strong>Notes to table 2:</strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><ul><li><p>Figures are rounded to the nearest £10.</p></li><li><p>The average award figures relate to the average payment net of returned payments (including appeals). This is calculated by taking the total value of payments in a given year (net of returned payments) and dividing by the total number of payments in a given year, as recorded in the Policy, Budget and Management Information System.</p></li><li><p>These averages include awards made after review, reconsideration or appeal following an initial refusal.</p></li></ul><p><strong> </strong></p><p>Data on the lowest FEP award in the years 2015-2018 is not collated centrally and could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p>","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse",,"2018-05-14T16:37:11.78Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/897242/answer","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/897242/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/897242/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-05-03","Funeral Payments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many applications for Social Fund funeral payments were made in each year between 2015 and 2018; how many such applications were refused; and what the (a) average and (b) lowest payment that was made.","false","Biography information for Mrs Emma Lewell-Buck","South Shields","Mrs Emma Lewell-Buck","141028"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/897243","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-05-14","<p>Data on Social Fund Budgeting Loans, where the loan is used to cover funeral costs, is not collated centrally and could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p><p>The average Social Fund Budgeting Loan payment in each of the last 5 years is provided in table 1. These relate to all Budgeting Loans and not just those used to cover funeral costs.</p><p> </p><p>Figures are rounded to the nearest £10.</p><p> </p><p><strong>Table 1: Average Budgeting Loan payments, 2013-2017</strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>2016</p></td><td><p>2017</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Average Budgeting Loan payment</p></td><td><p>£400</p></td><td><p>£410</p></td><td><p>£420</p></td><td><p>£430</p></td><td><p>£420</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Source: Policy, Budget and Management Information System</p><p> </p><p>In each of the last 5 years, the lowest payment made for a Social Fund Budgeting Loan is £100. This is the minimum amount that can be applied for.</p>","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse",,"2018-05-14T16:34:46.937Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/897243/answer","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/897243/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/897243/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-05-03","Funeral Payments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many Social Fund Budgeting loans to cover funeral costs were (a) approved and (b) rejected in each of the last five years; and what the (a) average and (b) lowest payment was for a Social Fund Budgeting loans.","false","Biography information for Mrs Emma Lewell-Buck","South Shields","Mrs Emma Lewell-Buck","141029"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/897244","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-05-10","<p>The UK Space Agency is leading a cross-Government taskforce, working with engineering and space experts in the UK, to rapidly develop plans for a British Global Navigation Satellite System with the aim of launching our own system from the mid-2020s onwards. Value for money will be a key consideration of this taskforce.</p><p> </p><p>In the long term, we believe that such a system could be operated for around the same annual cost as the UK’s current contribution to the EU’s Galileo programme.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2018-05-10T14:33:52.93Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/897244/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/897244/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/897244/answer","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/897244/answer/previousversion/56906","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-05-03","Global Navigation Satellite Systems","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what estimate he has made of the (a) cost to the public purse and (b) time-scale for setting up a British Global Navigation Satellite System.","false","Biography information for Layla Moran","Oxford West and Abingdon","Layla Moran","141054"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/897245","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-05-10","<p>The UK will continue to be able to access the US Global Positioning System (GPS) but a British system would also provide vital freedom to act independently, increase resilience and enhance UK and Allied operations in the global context.</p><p> </p><p>A British system would be compatible with GPS, meaning that if either were subject to malicious attack, we could continue to provide crucial positioning information to the UK and her Allies.</p><p> </p><p>The redundancy provided by having multiple systems of ground infrastructure, increased numbers of satellite constellations and multiple secure and open signals would greatly increase our resilience.</p><p> </p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2018-05-10T14:34:25.937Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/897245/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/897245/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/897245/answer","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/897245/answer/previousversion/56907","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-05-03","Global Navigation Satellite Systems","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, with reference to the UK Space Agency's announcement on the development of a British Global Navigation Satellite System published on 2 May 2018, what contingency plans his Department has put in place in the event that the UK is denied access to data for satellite navigation.","false","Biography information for Layla Moran","Oxford West and Abingdon","Layla Moran","141055"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/897246","Department for Education","false","2018-05-11","<p>In relation to identification of children with dyslexia and training for teachers to identify children with dyslexia, I refer the hon. Member for South Shields to the answer I gave on 3 May 2018 to Question <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2018-04-26/138480/" target="_blank">138480</a>.</p><p> </p><p>The framework of core content for Initial Teacher Training sets out that providers should ensure that trainees are equipped to identify the needs of all pupils, and make provision for them, including seeking the advice of colleagues with specialist knowledge and experience. Trainees should be able to recognise signs that may indicate special educational needs and disability (SEND), and support common educational needs through review of their teaching, making adjustments to overcome any barriers to progress and ensuring that pupils with SEND are able to access the curriculum.</p><p> </p><p>Since 2010, the department has funded the development of resources and training to ensure that the schools workforce is equipped to support pupils with specific types of SEND, including dyslexia. They have produced a wealth of resources and training which are hosted on the SEND Gateway.</p><p> </p><p>From April 2016 to March 2018, we funded the British Dyslexia Association with £1.25 million to deliver training to teachers, ‎to support early identification of learning difficulties, including dyslexia. Our new contract, which will be delivered by the Whole School Send Consortium over two years, brings together schools, SEND sector organisations and experts to ensure schools are equipped to deliver high-quality teaching that supports children with all kinds of SEND. The value for year one is £1.9 million and the value for year two is £1.5 million inclusive of VAT.</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi","141032","2018-05-11T17:11:28.01Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/897246/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/897246/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/897246/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-05-03","Pupils: Dyslexia","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what pathways his Department has established at schools for the identification of children with dyslexia.","false","Biography information for Mrs Emma Lewell-Buck","South Shields","Mrs Emma Lewell-Buck","141030"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/897247","Department for Education","false","2018-05-14","<p>We publish the number and proportion of pupils with special educational needs (SEN), including the type of need in the annual ‘Special educational needs in England’ statistical release. This is available at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/statistics-special-educational-needs-sen" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/statistics-special-educational-needs-sen</a>.</p><p> </p><p>SEN pupils are recorded according to their primary type of need. The current types of need do not include a specific breakdown for autism alone. These cases are expected to be recorded under ‘Autistic Spectrum Disorder’. No estimates of the number of children with autism within this category have been made.</p><p> </p><p>The current types of need do not include a specific breakdown for dyslexia alone. These cases are expected to be recorded under ‘Specific Learning Difficulty’. No estimates of the number of children with dyslexia within this category have been made.</p><p> </p><p>The table below shows a breakdown of the number of pupils by each primary type of need available for the last five years (as at January each year).</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Statements of SEN (and EHC plans from 2015)</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2013</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2014</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2015</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2016</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2017</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Specific Learning Difficulty</p></td><td><p>10,480</p></td><td><p>10,045</p></td><td><p>9,665</p></td><td><p>8,938</p></td><td><p>8,390</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Moderate Learning Difficulty</p></td><td><p>33,455</p></td><td><p>32,410</p></td><td><p>31,155</p></td><td><p>29,650</p></td><td><p>28,564</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Severe Learning Difficulty</p></td><td><p>27,540</p></td><td><p>28,330</p></td><td><p>28,940</p></td><td><p>29,001</p></td><td><p>29,120</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Profound &amp; Multiple Learning Difficulty</p></td><td><p>9,715</p></td><td><p>9,810</p></td><td><p>10,010</p></td><td><p>9,955</p></td><td><p>10,010</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Behaviour, Emotional &amp; Social Difficulties</p></td><td><p>29,960</p></td><td><p>30,035</p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Social, Emotional and Mental Health</p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p>28,135</p></td><td><p>27,259</p></td><td><p>28,007</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Speech, Language and Communications Needs</p></td><td><p>29,565</p></td><td><p>30,035</p></td><td><p>30,880</p></td><td><p>30,942</p></td><td><p>32,292</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Hearing Impairment</p></td><td><p>6,285</p></td><td><p>6,180</p></td><td><p>6,100</p></td><td><p>5,937</p></td><td><p>5,985</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Visual Impairment</p></td><td><p>3,540</p></td><td><p>3,490</p></td><td><p>3,450</p></td><td><p>3,330</p></td><td><p>3,239</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Multi- Sensory Impairment</p></td><td><p>525</p></td><td><p>550</p></td><td><p>610</p></td><td><p>631</p></td><td><p>686</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Physical Disability</p></td><td><p>13,345</p></td><td><p>13,080</p></td><td><p>13,025</p></td><td><p>12,873</p></td><td><p>12,742</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Autistic Spectrum Disorder</p></td><td><p>47,225</p></td><td><p>49,975</p></td><td><p>54,245</p></td><td><p>57,211</p></td><td><p>60,832</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Other Difficulty/Disability</p></td><td><p>4,395</p></td><td><p>4,540</p></td><td><p>5,150</p></td><td><p>5,228</p></td><td><p>5,727</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>SEN Support but no specialist assessment</p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p>285</p></td><td><p>268</p></td><td><p>359</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Total</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>216,030</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>218,475</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>221,650</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>221,223</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>225,953</strong></p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>Note: The figures provided have been rounded in line with their presentation in the statistics publication 'Special educational needs in England'. Figures are rounded to the nearest five for year 2013 to 2015. No rounding is applied for 2016 onwards.</p><p>Source: School Census</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi","141035","2018-05-14T16:49:49.077Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/897247/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/897247/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/897247/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-05-03","Pupils: Dyslexia","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what comparative estimate he has made of the number of school children with dyslexia who were subject to (a) education, health and care plans and (b) statements under the previous SEN and learning difficulties assessments in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Mrs Emma Lewell-Buck","South Shields","Mrs Emma Lewell-Buck","141031"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/897248","Department for Education","false","2018-05-11","<p>In relation to identification of children with dyslexia and training for teachers to identify children with dyslexia, I refer the hon. Member for South Shields to the answer I gave on 3 May 2018 to Question <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2018-04-26/138480/" target="_blank">138480</a>.</p><p> </p><p>The framework of core content for Initial Teacher Training sets out that providers should ensure that trainees are equipped to identify the needs of all pupils, and make provision for them, including seeking the advice of colleagues with specialist knowledge and experience. Trainees should be able to recognise signs that may indicate special educational needs and disability (SEND), and support common educational needs through review of their teaching, making adjustments to overcome any barriers to progress and ensuring that pupils with SEND are able to access the curriculum.</p><p> </p><p>Since 2010, the department has funded the development of resources and training to ensure that the schools workforce is equipped to support pupils with specific types of SEND, including dyslexia. They have produced a wealth of resources and training which are hosted on the SEND Gateway.</p><p> </p><p>From April 2016 to March 2018, we funded the British Dyslexia Association with £1.25 million to deliver training to teachers, ‎to support early identification of learning difficulties, including dyslexia. Our new contract, which will be delivered by the Whole School Send Consortium over two years, brings together schools, SEND sector organisations and experts to ensure schools are equipped to deliver high-quality teaching that supports children with all kinds of SEND. The value for year one is £1.9 million and the value for year two is £1.5 million inclusive of VAT.</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi","141030","2018-05-11T17:11:28.073Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/897248/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/897248/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/897248/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-05-03","Pupils: Dyslexia","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, whether his Department provides training for teachers to identify dyslexia in primary school children.","false","Biography information for Mrs Emma Lewell-Buck","South Shields","Mrs Emma Lewell-Buck","141032"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/897249","Department for Education","false","2018-05-14","<p>Due to the wide range of abilities of individual children and young people, we do not set a separate pathway for identification specific conditions such as autism. Instead, we require schools to assess a pupil’s needs as soon as they become aware that they are not achieving their potential.</p><p> </p><p>The pupil’s teacher and the school’s Special Educational Needs Coordinator (SENCO) should involve other teachers and should include the views and experience of the pupil, their parents or carers and any relevant external supporting information. If they identify a need for special educational support, they must formally notify the parents or carers and agree what adjustments, interventions or support will be put in place in a support plan. The subject teacher then is responsible for implementing the plan on a daily basis. The school should review the impact and progress made by the planned date and provide further support as needed. This “Assess, Plan, Do, and Review” cycle is set out for schools in detail in paragraphs 6.36-6.56, in the statutory ‘Special educational needs and disability code of practice: 0 to 25 years’ available at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/send-code-of-practice-0-to-25" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/send-code-of-practice-0-to-25</a>.</p><p> </p><p>In terms of training for teachers to identify autism in primary schools, we have contracted with the Autism Education Trust to deliver training to staff in, early years schools (primary and secondary) and colleges. The 2018-2020 contract builds on previous contracts providing “whole school” autism training since 2012 for a wide range of staff and not just teachers. More than 150,000 staff have been trained to date.</p><p> </p><p>From July 2016 Initial Teacher Training includes specific special educational needs and disabilities content, including on autism.</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi","141034","2018-05-14T16:23:59.553Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/897249/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/897249/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/897249/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-05-03","Pupils: Autism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what pathways his Department has established at schools for the identification of children with autism in schools.","false","Biography information for Mrs Emma Lewell-Buck","South Shields","Mrs Emma Lewell-Buck","141033"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/897250","Department for Education","false","2018-05-14","<p>Due to the wide range of abilities of individual children and young people, we do not set a separate pathway for identification specific conditions such as autism. Instead, we require schools to assess a pupil’s needs as soon as they become aware that they are not achieving their potential.</p><p> </p><p>The pupil’s teacher and the school’s Special Educational Needs Coordinator (SENCO) should involve other teachers and should include the views and experience of the pupil, their parents or carers and any relevant external supporting information. If they identify a need for special educational support, they must formally notify the parents or carers and agree what adjustments, interventions or support will be put in place in a support plan. The subject teacher then is responsible for implementing the plan on a daily basis. The school should review the impact and progress made by the planned date and provide further support as needed. This “Assess, Plan, Do, and Review” cycle is set out for schools in detail in paragraphs 6.36-6.56, in the statutory ‘Special educational needs and disability code of practice: 0 to 25 years’ available at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/send-code-of-practice-0-to-25" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/send-code-of-practice-0-to-25</a>.</p><p> </p><p>In terms of training for teachers to identify autism in primary schools, we have contracted with the Autism Education Trust to deliver training to staff in, early years schools (primary and secondary) and colleges. The 2018-2020 contract builds on previous contracts providing “whole school” autism training since 2012 for a wide range of staff and not just teachers. More than 150,000 staff have been trained to date.</p><p> </p><p>From July 2016 Initial Teacher Training includes specific special educational needs and disabilities content, including on autism.</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi","141033","2018-05-14T16:23:59.6Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/897250/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/897250/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/897250/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-05-03","Pupils: Autism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, whether his Department provides training for teachers to identify autism in primary school children.","false","Biography information for Mrs Emma Lewell-Buck","South Shields","Mrs Emma Lewell-Buck","141034"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/897251","Department for Education","false","2018-05-14","<p>We publish the number and proportion of pupils with special educational needs (SEN), including the type of need in the annual ‘Special educational needs in England’ statistical release. This is available at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/statistics-special-educational-needs-sen" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/statistics-special-educational-needs-sen</a>.</p><p> </p><p>SEN pupils are recorded according to their primary type of need. The current types of need do not include a specific breakdown for autism alone. These cases are expected to be recorded under ‘Autistic Spectrum Disorder’. No estimates of the number of children with autism within this category have been made.</p><p> </p><p>The current types of need do not include a specific breakdown for dyslexia alone. These cases are expected to be recorded under ‘Specific Learning Difficulty’. No estimates of the number of children with dyslexia within this category have been made.</p><p> </p><p>The table below shows a breakdown of the number of pupils by each primary type of need available for the last five years (as at January each year).</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Statements of SEN (and EHC plans from 2015)</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2013</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2014</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2015</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2016</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2017</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Specific Learning Difficulty</p></td><td><p>10,480</p></td><td><p>10,045</p></td><td><p>9,665</p></td><td><p>8,938</p></td><td><p>8,390</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Moderate Learning Difficulty</p></td><td><p>33,455</p></td><td><p>32,410</p></td><td><p>31,155</p></td><td><p>29,650</p></td><td><p>28,564</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Severe Learning Difficulty</p></td><td><p>27,540</p></td><td><p>28,330</p></td><td><p>28,940</p></td><td><p>29,001